	<heading>Programming Resources</heading>
	
	<p>Here are a list of existing educational resources for learning to program. This list covers many different languages. It does not attempt to be a comprehensive list &mdash; instead it is simply a collection of the best resources I can find for each language.</p>
	
	<p>I think that <a href="http://norvig.com/21-days.html">this</a> is particularly relevant when considering the below material.</p>
	
	<table class="basic">
		<thead>
			<tr>
				<th>Resource</th>
				<th>Description</th>
			</tr>
		</thead>
		<tbody>
			<!-- Finding up to date C / C++ resources was exceptionally difficult -->
			<tr><th>C / C++</th></tr>
			<tr>
				<td><a href="http://cprog.tomsweb.net/cintro.html">An introduction to C</a></td>
				<td>An extensive tutorial covering many C features.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><a href="http://www.cplusplus.com/doc/tutorial/introduction/">C++ Language Tutorial</a></td>
				<td>A beginner guide to programming in C++.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><a href="http://www.relisoft.com/book/index.htm">C++ In Action</a></td>
				<td>An online book covering many C++ features from a beginner to intermediate perspective.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><a href="http://www.network-theory.co.uk/docs/gccintro/index.html">An Introduction to GCC</a></td>
				<td>A manual that provides an introduction to the GNU C and C++ compilers.</td>
			</tr>
			
